Inflamm Bowel Dis
    Colonic Epithelial Circadian Disruption Worsens Dextran Sulfate Sodium-Induced Colitis.
Disruption of intestinal circadian rhythms in colonic epithelial cells promoted more severe colitis, increased inflammatory mediators (STAT3 [signal transducer and activator of transcription 3]), and decreased gut microbiota-derived SCFAs compared with DSS alone. Further investigation elucidating the molecular mechanisms behind these findings could provide novel circadian directed targets and strategies in the treatment of inflammatory bowel disease.
Pubmed   Journal   ReadQx 
Creation of an Inflammatory Bowel Disease Referral Pathway for Identifying Patients Who Would Benefit From Inflammatory Bowel Disease Specialist Consultation.
This novel referral care pathway identifies key criteria that could be used to triage patients with IBD who would benefit from IBD specialist consultation. Future research will be required to validate these findings and assess the impact of implementing this pathway in routine IBD-related care.
Pubmed   Journal   ReadQx 
Deletion of Smad7 Ameliorates Intestinal Inflammation and Contributes to Fibrosis.
Smad7 deficiency is associated with a decrease in intestinal inflammation and an increase in fibrosis. Targeting SMAD7 constitutes a potential new treatment option for IBD;  progression of disease-associated fibrosis should be considered.
Pubmed   Journal   ReadQx 
Hypoxic ASCs-derived Exosomes Attenuate Colitis by Regulating Macrophage Polarization via miR-216a-5p/HMGB1 Axis.
Exosomal miR-216a-5p released from hypoxia-prime ASCs showed higher therapeutic efficiency than NExos in experimental colitis by promoting the M2 macrophage phenotype, which indicated that hypoxia prime may represent a promising approach to optimizing the function of ASC-derived exosomes.
Pubmed   Journal   ReadQx 
Opioid Legislation in Patients With Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A State-wide Retrospective Cohort Study.
Despite legislation and the increased use of disease-modifying drugs, statewide opioid prescriptions continued to increase. The increase in opiate use, high steroid use, and significant health care utilization suggests poor underlying disease control.
